  "theory": {
    "canonical_statement": "ID 444 defines the thermal stabilization of the reactor using High Temperature Superconductors (HTS) like YBCO (Yttrium Barium Copper Oxide). While the vacuum remains at the UHV limit, the external housing is immersed in a liquid nitrogen (LN2 ) jacket. This configuration allows the system to maintain the superconducting gap () required for energy extraction while effectively dissipating the Landauer heat generated by the 12 node array. Resilience: YBCO provides superior operation at accessible temperatures compared to niobium. Gradient Control: Minimized thermal gradients are essential to prevent noise in the weak measurement record.",
    "technical_interpretation": "ID 444 defines the thermal stabilization of the reactor using High Temperature Superconductors (HTS) like YBCO (Yttrium Barium Copper Oxide). While the vacuum remains at the UHV limit, the external housing is immersed in a liquid nitrogen (LN2 ) jacket. This configuration allows the system to maintain the superconducting gap () required for energy extraction while effectively dissipating the Landauer heat generated by the 12 node array. Resilience: YBCO provides superior operation at accessible temperatures compared to niobium. Gradient Control: Minimized thermal gradients are essential to prevent noise in the weak measurement record."
